The new anti-globalization reaction
PRINCETON – A palpable sense of unease was felt during the last G-7 summit in Ise-Shima, Japan.
At the next meeting of leaders of the world's major developed economies, no one can say which of them will be part of the populist insurgents.
President Donald Trump could represent the United States, or President Marine Le Pen could represent France.
They could sit with British Prime Minister Boris Johnson, Italian Prime Minister Beppe Grillo, or even with German Chancellor Frauke Petry.
Each of them could become the champion of nationalism and isolationism, in one form or another.
The reaction against globalization has been going on for two decades.
At the end of the 20th century, the global trend seemed to be toward convergence and people appeared to be consuming the same products everywhere.
McDonald's illustrated this kind of globalization: closing down stores in this chain became a standard form of protest against globalization.
But recently, the nature of globalization has changed, as has the reaction against it.
Although the world is still becoming more interconnected, there is a feeling that we understand less foreigners.
In response to the evolution of consumer preferences (which are increasingly more specialized), companies are relocating their production closer to the markets where the goods will be sold.
This weakens the growth of international trade.
Such an "on-shore" anchoring is not new.
In the 1970s and 1980s, Americans feared that the United States would be flooded with Japanese cars. They then began producing these cars domestically.
Currently, most "Japanese" cars sold in the United States are actually manufactured in the United States. But the reversal of globalization in goods is now easier than ever, thanks to advances in robotic engineering and the development of processes like 3D printing.
Thus, the current critique of globalization tends to focus less on commercial issues.
But this shift does not reflect only the slowing growth of trade.
Consumers in wealthy countries are far more comfortable with foreign products, and in some cases even dependent on them, from constantly updated electronics to "fashionable" low-cost items, which have become dominant in advanced economies.
Instead of rejecting foreign products, today's opponents of globalization reject foreigners.
Disputes over investor protection clauses in trade agreements such as the Trans-Pacific Partnership or the Transatlantic Partnership for Trade and Investment focus on the problems of obscure tribunals protecting the interests of foreign companies and alleged threats to national sovereignty.
Then there is the global refugee crisis: in Europe, in particular, the anxiety over this influx may be a warning sign of a broader rejection of immigration from failing and impoverished states.
Why are people in advanced countries so afraid of foreigners?
It's not as if they have never been exposed to other cultures.
Many citizens of these countries travel constantly to distant destinations, and hundreds of millions of people around the world travel to advanced countries each year.
The problem lies in the way we travel.
Today, we are more inclined to experience things quickly and superficially, rather than immerse ourselves in a culture.
But as modern game theory teaches us, a single interaction is very different from continuous contact.
If participants know they have a unique and limited experience, they have no interest in building a deeper base of understanding or cooperation.
Continuous exchange is necessary to foster trust.
The result of the superficial approach to current travel is evident for any major tourist destination.
Restaurants are reluctant to provide good or even honest service to people who will surely never return.
Restaurants serve mediocre (or worse) food without a smile, taxi drivers cheat you, and hoteliers lie about their facilities.
In addition, this little game can be disrupted.
On sites where tourism has become a source of foreign revenue, it also becomes a tempting target for terrorists who base their ideology on anti-Western resentment.
Some attacks in places like Bali or the tourist complexes of the Red Sea are enough to cause deep economic destabilization.
Tourism companies respond to such risks by minimizing contact with the local population.
The emblem of modern tourism is a gigantic cruise ship, where passengers can spend a few hours at each destination (to visit a beautiful Caribbean island or an ancient Mediterranean port), but always sleep in the same bed.
The new ship Harmony of the Seas by Royal Caribbean aims to recreate all the climates of the world.
In fact, this ship, longer than the Eiffel Tower, contains a tropical garden and an ice rink (in addition to its 23 pools and 42 bars).
Tourist bus and train companies do the same to ensure the safety of their customers, releasing them only for a limited time on a famous site, just long enough to take a few photos.
This style of travel imposes a constraint on the capacity of local infrastructure.
There is often a lack of space to walk along the canals of Venice or on the path leading to the Acropolis.
This approach reinforces mutual misunderstanding.
Visitors stay within the limits of their pre-planned tours, encountering only scammers who offer trinkets or overpriced taxi rides.
Indigenous people do not appreciate tourist groups gathering around their most beautiful sites.
No one feels particularly involved, nor is there any sense of trust.
It is easy to feel nostalgic for the time when tourism went hand in hand with long stays and extended encounters with very different cultures.
It would obviously be impossible, given the current number of visitors, to stay for weeks or months in old monasteries.
But it is possible to imagine certain configurations in which visitors and their hosts could interact in a more personal way.
Airbnb, for example, can provide a much more attractive experience than a hotel or, worse, a cruise ship.
Is there a policy equivalent to Airbnb?
Could world leaders participate in summits like the G-7, living and working for an extended period in a foreign country?
Shortly after the United States entered World War II, Winston Churchill made the famous gesture of setting up camp to reside at the White House for 24 days, in order to strengthen the transatlantic alliance of Britain by deepening his relationship with Franklin Roosevelt.
This level of familiarity could well be the greatest enemy of today's anti-globalist populists.
